{"parentUuid":"e07805f7-c98c-45cb-be64-4b81c22de9f4","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9da69fb9296f48e1","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_0146bMmrWdhtbGTzkVA9gAm3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The question asks which reference to consult first for deleting one entry from `PositionOutput` (a merge table) via a merge_key. The two most relevant references are `destructive_operations.md` (deletion safety) and `merge_methods.md` (merge-table-specific APIs like `merge_get_part`, `delete` on parents). For a merge-table delete via merge_key, `merge_methods.md` is the primary reference because the merge_key delete pattern is merge-specific — but `destructive_operations.md` covers the safety workflow that wraps any delete."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":186,"cache_read_input_tokens":22560,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":186,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CaWYG56U1Ktjk7Kx1MPWA","type":"assistant","uuid":"7f062e65-b82a-4489-b98d-09d885fb4a47","timestamp":"2026-04-28T17:10:22.512Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"/Users/edeno/Documents/GitHub/spyglass-skill","sessionId":"1f8c4ccf-12e2-4179-973b-7ba51de72be5","version":"2.1.119","gitBranch":"master","slug":"rippling-forging-crane"}
{"parentUuid":"7f062e65-b82a-4489-b98d-09d885fb4a47","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9da69fb9296f48e1","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_0146bMmrWdhtbGTzkVA9gAm3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017uBFVtJR9MfMNYKmwsEnuV","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/edeno/Documents/GitHub/spyglass-skill/skills/spyglass-workspace/iteration-7/eval-066-resource-first-ref-merge-delete/without_skill/outputs/response.md","content":"# Which reference do I consult first?\n\nFor deleting a single entry from `PositionOutput` via a `merge_key`, you have two references in play, and the order matters:\n\n1. **First: `references/destructive_operations.md`**\n   Any `.delete()` against a Spyglass table is a destructive cascade. The destructive-operations reference is the resource-first stop because it covers the safety workflow that has to wrap *any* delete:\n   - restrict before deleting (never call `.delete()` on an unrestricted table),\n   - preview the cascade with `.delete(safemode=True)` / inspect downstream descendants,\n   - confirm row count is what you expect (exactly 1 here),\n   - understand transaction semantics and what gets cascaded into part tables and downstream merges.\n   This applies whether the target is a merge table or a regular table, so it sets the guardrails before you touch the merge-specific API.\n\n2. **Second: `references/merge_methods.md`**\n   Merge tables have their own delete idioms because the row you want to remove lives in a *part table* (e.g. `PositionOutput.TrodesPosV1`), not in the `PositionOutput` master directly. The merge-methods reference is where you find:\n   - how `merge_key` (the `merge_id` UUID) maps to the correct part table,\n   - `PositionOutput.merge_get_part(restriction)` to resolve the part-table row from a merge_key,\n   - the recommended pattern of restricting the part table by the `merge_id` and calling `.delete()` there (deleting from the master alone can leave orphaned part rows or fail the FK cascade in the wrong order),\n   - any helper like `delete_downstream_parts` / `delete_downstream_merge` that Spyglass exposes for merge cleanup.\n\n## Concrete order of operations\n\n```text\ndestructive_operations.md   -> safety workflow, safemode preview, cascade awareness\nmerge_methods.md            -> merge_get_part + part-table restrict-then-delete pattern\n```\n\nSo: open `destructive_operations.md` first to lock in the safety workflow, then `merge_methods.md` for the merge-key-specific delete mechanics. If `PositionOutput` itself is feeding a downstream pipeline (e.g. linearization, decoding) you may also need a quick look at `dependencies.md` to confirm what the cascade will sweep, but those are the two primary references.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":186,"cache_read_input_tokens":22560,"output_tokens":1120,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":186},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":1120,"cache_read_input_tokens":22560,"cache_creation_input_tokens":186,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":186,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CaWYG56U1Ktjk7Kx1MPWA","type":"assistant","uuid":"bfb6ee99-f5ea-4a36-866e-205c6af178e1","timestamp":"2026-04-28T17:10:37.421Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"/Users/edeno/Documents/GitHub/spyglass-skill","sessionId":"1f8c4ccf-12e2-4179-973b-7ba51de72be5","version":"2.1.119","gitBranch":"master","slug":"rippling-forging-crane"}
